// Step 1: Import React and ReactDOM
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';

// Step 2: Create a component
function Greeting() {
  return <h1>Hello, React!</h1>;
}

// Step 3: Find the DOM node to render into
const rootElement = document.getElementById('root');

// Step 4: Create a root and render
const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(rootElement);
root.render(<Greeting />);

// That's it! Your component is now live!

## The App Component

Every React application has a top-level **App** component that contains everything else:

```javascript
// App.jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <header>
        <h1>My Website</h1>
      </header>
      <main>
        <p>Welcome to my app!</p>
      </main>
      <footer>
        <p>© 2024</p>
      </footer>
    </div>
  );
}

// index.js (entry point)
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
import App from './App';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
root.render(<App />);
```

**Why use an App component?**
- Single entry point for your entire UI
- Easy to manage and organize
- Can hold global providers later (Context, Router, etc.)

// index.js - Application Entry Point
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
import App from './App';

// Get the root element from HTML
const container = document.getElementById('root');

// Create a React root
const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(container);

// Render the App component
root.render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <App />
  </React.StrictMode>
);

## How React Renders Efficiently

### What is the Virtual DOM?

The **Virtual DOM** is a lightweight copy of the real DOM that React keeps in memory.

### How It Works:

1. **Initial Render**: React creates the Virtual DOM and copies it to the Real DOM

2. **State Change**: When state changes, React creates a NEW Virtual DOM

3. **Diffing**: React compares the new Virtual DOM with the old one

4. **Selective Update**: React only updates the parts of the Real DOM that changed

### Why This Matters:

```javascript
// Without React (traditional approach):
// Update EVERYTHING (slow!)
document.getElementById('count').textContent = newCount;

// With React:
// Only updates what changed (fast!)
setCount(newCount);
```

The Virtual DOM makes React applications **fast** even with frequent updates!

// You can compose multiple components together

function Header() {
  return <header><h1>My Site</h1></header>;
}

function MainContent() {
  return <main><p>Hello!</p></main>;
}

function Footer() {
  return <footer><p>Goodbye!</p></footer>;
}

// Compose them in App
function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <MainContent />
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}

// Render the whole thing
root.render(<App />);

// Result: All components render together!

**Only call `root.render()` once** at the start of your application:

```javascript
// ✅ Correct - render once
root.render(<App />);

// ❌ Wrong - don't re-render manually
root.render(<App />);
root.render(<App />); // Don't do this!
```

To update what's displayed, **change state**, not the render call. React handles re-rendering automatically!

